     <font class="TallRed">Can someone please bottle this!<a name="109172170805497932">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          What is it about Bob? I have been having the most fucked up week, nonstop stress everywhere I turn. So I get into work today, I have launchcast playing, and Bob comes on.... What is it about this music that soothes my soul. I swear, I can be in the worst fucking mood imaginable, and it just goes away. You just can't be upset and listen to Reggae, even when the song makes you sadder, it is more like a cleansing sadness, kind like crying it out if that makes any sense. Of all the music that came out in the 20th Century, Time magazine voted Bob Marley Exodus as the album of the century and I think they really are onto something. No matter what you think of the music, you have to admit one thing, it is powerful. I have said before, these three guys in a slum in Trenchtown Jamaica, what amounts to a speck of dirt in the ocean, bascially invent this new genre of music and end up turning the world on its ear. I wonder if they would have ever thought their music would have such far reaching implications. From Clapton remaking I shot the Sheriff, to the Police, UB40, Madness and the Clash in England during the 70's and 80's, and on into the 90's with Sublime, No Doubt, the Ziggins, and of course 311. I wonder what Bob Marley would have said in the early 60's if someone had told him a bunch of lily ass white boys in a basement in OMAHA NEBRASKA of all places, would dig his sound and help launch the third wave of reggae. If anyone has ever seen Marley performing, on video of course, it is amazing, to say it makes me jealous would be a huge understatement. Some artist simply have a connection with what they are doing that gives them an almost deity kind of status. It is like watcing a Shaman performing rituals. Hendrix, Marley, Morrison, etc.. you get the feeling watching them that if they were in a room by themselves playing for the walls, that they would be just as intense. Anyway, I am in a great mood today and wanted to share.. LOL  I also found out this morning that Jimmy Cliff is going to be at the State Theater next Wed.. So of course it will be me and as many Red Stripes as I can pour down my throat. Hehehehe as I wrap this up, Toots and the Maytals are playing... 54-46 Thats My Number... Yes Sublime remade it, 75% of Sublime's catalog are remakes.<br /><br />Oh, and the growth of that genre from absolute obscurity, happened long before there was an internet and many other widely available forms of mass communication.<br /><br />
